{
  "text": "Our results are consistent with data implicating the prefrontal cortex in emotion regulation, a process that is perturbed in BPD. Reductions in amygdala and accumbens volumes are consistent with neuropsychological data on pediatric BPD. Further study is required to determine the relationship between these findings in children and adults with BPD. Psychiatry. 2005; 62:734-741 P EDIATRIC BIPOLAR DISORDER (BPD) is currently one of the most active and controversial areas of clinical and research interest in child psychiatry. Investigators have systematically described the clinical presentation of pediatric BPD and are now exploring neural mechanisms that might mediate the symptoms of the illness. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] One approach to such pathophysiologic research is to use neuropsychological tests to implicate specific brain regions whose function might be impaired in children with BPD, and then to follow up on these behavioral results with neuroimaging studies.",
